href="tomdejong.xml"
type="local"
addr="tomdejong">Tom de Jong</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="martinescardo.xml"
type="local"
addr="martinescardo">Martín Hötzel Escardó</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> be a <fr:link
href="jms-0023.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0023">positively generated</fr:link> <fr:link
href="jms-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-001S">pointed</fr:link> dcpo; then <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is canonically <fr:em>free</fr:em> on its <fr:link
href="jms-001P.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-001P">subdcpo of positive elements</fr:link> <fr:tex>A^+</fr:tex>. More specifically, the embedding-projection pair <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathsf { L } { \iota ^+}; \alpha _A \right ) \mathclose {}} \dashv { A } \xrightarrow {{ \mathsf { purify } _A }}{ \mathsf { L } {A^+} }</fr:tex> <fr:link
href="jms-0020.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0020">given by</fr:link> the <fr:link
href="jms-0021.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0021">purification map</fr:link> is an isomorphism of dcpos.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
