type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-002A</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>First, we recall that the embedding-projection pair <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathsf { L } { \iota ^+}; \alpha _A \right ) \mathclose {}} \dashv \mathsf { purify } _A</fr:tex> <fr:link
href="jms-0020.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0020">exists</fr:link> because <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> has an <fr:link
href="jms-0022.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0022">open positivity predicate</fr:link> by <fr:link
href="jms-0027.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0027">virtue of</fr:link> its <fr:link
href="jms-0023.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0023">positive generation</fr:link>. Therefore, the statement of this lemma is well-formed.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>Because <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathsf { L } { \iota ^+}; \alpha _A \right ) \mathclose {}} \dashv \mathsf { purify } _A</fr:tex> is an embedding-projection pair, it remains only to check that <fr:tex>\mathsf { purify } _A; \mathsf { L } { \iota ^+}; \alpha _A</fr:tex> is an <fr:em>inflation</fr:em>, i.e. for all <fr:tex>a:A</fr:tex> we must have <fr:tex>a  \sqsubseteq   \alpha _A { \mathopen {} \left ( \mathsf { L } { \iota ^+} { \mathopen {} \left ( \mathsf { purify } _Aa \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>. As the latter is equal to <fr:tex>\bigsqcup _{p: \mathsf { pos } \, a}a</fr:tex>, the inflation condition follows from our assumption that <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-0023.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0023">positively generated</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
